\chapter{Process Description}

\section{Steam Methane Reforming (SMR).} 

Steam methane reforming is the dominant industrial route for hydrogen (H\textsubscript{2}) production, converting methane (CH\textsubscript{4}) and steam (H\textsubscript{2}O) into a hydrogen-rich syngas through a catalytic reaction \cite{RostrupNielsen1993,RostrupNielsen2011}. Methane (CH\textsubscript{4}) and steam (H\textsubscript{2}O) are blended and preheated to the reaction activation temperature in a feed preheater \cite{RostrupNielsen1993,Haussinger2011}. The preheated mixture is then fed to the primary reformer, where the reforming reaction takes place. The reaction is endothermic, requiring continuous external heating of the reformer. The reformer outlet stream is a syngas mixture containing hydrogen (H\textsubscript{2}), carbon monoxide (CO), unreacted methane (CH\textsubscript{4}), and residual steam (H\textsubscript{2}O) \cite{RostrupNielsen1993,IEAGHG2017}.

\section{Water-Gas Shift (WGS).}

The reformer effluent is cooled in a process-gas cooler before entering the water-gas shift reactor, where additional hydrogen (H\textsubscript{2}) is generated by reacting carbon monoxide (CO) with steam (H\textsubscript{2}O) \cite{Haussinger2011,Newsome1980}. The reactor effluent contains hydrogen (H\textsubscript{2}), carbon dioxide (CO\textsubscript{2}), unreacted methane (CH\textsubscript{4}), residual water (H\textsubscript{2}O), and small amounts of unconverted carbon monoxide (CO) \cite{Newsome1980, Ratnasamy2009}. The stream is cooled further to condense the residual water (H\textsubscript{2}O), which is removed in a gas-liquid separator \cite{RostrupNielsen2011}. The remaining dry gas advances to a hydrogen-separation unit, where hydrogen (H\textsubscript{2}) is recovered as the main product, and a carbon-dioxide-rich (CO\textsubscript{2}) tail gas is routed to the capture section \cite{IEAGHG2017, Sircar2000}.

\section{Downstream Processing and CO\textsubscript{2} Compression.}

 The off-gas from the pressure swing adsorption (PSA) unit is cooled and routed to the gas-liquid (GL) separator, where residual water (H\textsubscript{2}O) is removed and the remaining gas phase containing carbon monoxide (CO), carbon dioxide (CO\textsubscript{2}), and unreacted methane (CH\textsubscript{4})  is sent to the compound separator for further processing \cite{RostrupNielsen2011, Sircar2000}. In the compound separator, carbon dioxide (CO\textsubscript{2}) is selectively separated from the gas mixture for capture and storage, while the residual gas stream containing carbon monoxide (CO) and methane (CH\textsubscript{4}) is recovered for further use\cite{IEAGHG2017,Kohl1997}. The separated carbon dioxide (CO\textsubscript{2}) stream is then compressed in a three-stage compressor with interstage cooling to achieve the supercritical pressure required for transport and final storage, while the remaining off-gas is preheated and recycled as fuel to the reformer to improve overall energy efficiency \cite{IPCC2005,Wang2011}.
